ShiftSync is a comprehensive workforce management platform designed specifically for frontline teams. It moves beyond static spreadsheets by integrating scheduling, attendance, payroll, and real-time communication into a single source of truth.

Features

1. User Onboarding & Identity Management
The app uses Clerk for authentication, supporting a multi-tenant architecture where users belong to specific Organisations.

Create or Join: New users either create a new organization (becoming the Admin) or join an existing one using a unique Organisation ID.
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC): Permissions are strictly enforced both on the frontend (UI visibility) and backend (middleware).
Admin: Full control over payroll, analytics, settings, and member roles.
Manager: Can manage shifts, approve swaps, and view audit logs, but typically cannot process payroll or view high-level financial analytics unless permitted.
Employee: Can view their schedule, clock in/out, request swaps, and message teammates.
2. Scheduling & Shift Lifecycle
Scheduling is the core of the app, managed via a Kanban-style interface.

Shift Creation: Managers create shifts with titles, locations, and color tags. The backend performs SQL-level conflict detection to ensure an employee isn't double-booked.
Status Workflow: Shifts move through a lifecycle: OPEN (unassigned) → ASSIGNED → IN_PROGRESS (currently clocked in) → COMPLETED.
Real-time Updates: When a shift is created or updated, the change is broadcast via Socket.io to everyone in the organization, ensuring the roster is always up to date without page refreshes.
3. Real-Time Attendance Tracking
This feature connects the schedule to actual hours worked.

Clock In/Out: Employees see their "Ready to Clock In" shifts on the Attendance page. When they clock in, a CLOCK_IN event is recorded with a timestamp.
Live Attendance: Admins and Managers have a "Live Now" view. They can see exactly who is currently on shift, providing instant visibility into floor coverage.
Timesheets: Once an employee clocks out, the system calculates the duration. Employees can view their personal timesheet for the month to track their earned hours.
4. Shift Swapping Workflow
To handle the common problem of last-minute changes, ShiftSync provides a formal swap request system.

Requesting: An employee assigned to a shift can request a swap. They can either target a specific colleague or send the request to the "Open Pool."
Manager Approval: Requests appear on the Manager’s dashboard. Managers see the reason for the swap and can "Approve" or "Reject" with one click.
Auto-Update: Upon approval, the system automatically reassigns the shift to the new member and notifies both parties instantly.
5. Payroll, Rates & Overtime
Payroll is calculated automatically based on clock events, removing manual data entry.

Pay Periods: Admins define cycles (e.g., Bi-weekly).
Overtime Rules: The system applies daily (8h) and weekly (40h) thresholds. If an employee exceeds these, the "Overtime Multiplier" is applied to those specific hours.
Employee Rates: Each member has an hourly rate. Admins can set "Effective Dates" for rate changes, ensuring historical payroll remains accurate even if a person gets a raise mid-period.
Payslip Generation: Once a period is "Processed," the system generates a breakdown of base hours vs. OT hours. These are then available as downloadable PDFs.
6. Organizational Communication
Announcements: Admins can post "Global" or "Targeted" announcements.
Priority Levels: NORMAL, HIGH, or URGENT (marked with high-contrast UI).
Targeting: Announcements can be sent to the whole company or a specific individual (acting as a formal notification).
Direct Messaging: A peer-to-peer chat system allows team members to coordinate. It includes real-time typing indicators and unread message tracking.
7. Analytics & Business Intelligence
Exclusively for Admins, the Analytics dashboard provides a high-level view of organizational health.

Workforce Velocity: A bar chart comparing "Total Scheduled Shifts" vs. "Completed Shifts" to identify absenteeism or scheduling gaps.
Coverage Rate: A line chart showing what percentage of the required labor was actually met throughout the week.
Financial KPIs: Live tracking of Total Labor Cost and Total Hours Tracked for the current month.
8. Audit Logging & Accountability
Security and accountability are maintained through a detailed audit trail.

Traceability: Every "write" operation (creating a shift, deleting a member, changing a pay rate) is logged.
State Diffs: For updates, the system stores the "Before" and "After" JSON states, so Admins can see exactly what changed.
Metadata: Logs include the IP address and User Agent of the person who performed the action to prevent unauthorized access disputes.
9. The Real-Time Engine (Socket.io)
Under the hood, the app uses a dual-room socket strategy:

org:{id} Room: Used for broadcasts like new announcements, shift updates, and swap requests that the whole management team or staff needs to see.
user:{id} Room: Used for private events, such as direct messages or notifications specifically for that user (e.g., "Your swap request was approved").
